"script": "Every single day, the United States prints around 38 million banknotes worth roughly 1.5 billion dollars. Stacked flat, one day's printing would tower higher than a 30-story building. But here's the twist, most of those bills aren't new wealth at all, they're just replacing worn-out ones being shredded. In fact, the mint destroys tons of tattered cash every week, turning it into compost and landfill. And if you laid a single day's bills end to end, they'd stretch over 3,000 miles, reaching clear across the entire country, coast to coast, in fresh green paper.",
